metadata.name: Mondrian Chess #105
metadata.description:
This artwork unifies the visual aesthetics of Mondrian with the mathematical beauty of chess. Each piece is a unique piece, as its representation is re-generated for every piece.

While the colors seems to be random placed in the grid, they are not an expose the inner working of the artwork.

metadata.name: Kintsugi #110
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãloss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.

metadata.name: Celestial Objects #14
metadata.description:
Celestial Objects is a generative collection imagining planets and stars in the space, with light and shadows being key themes. 

The artwork is primarily rendered using hundreds of thousands of points (more than a million in some cases) to create different aspects of the output including the sky textures, shooting stars and shadows on the planets. 

Celestial Objects is coded in p5.js, and please note that it takes 5-15 seconds for each output to render.

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)
